---
import ElevationLayout from '../../layouts/ElevationLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../../components/elevation/Hero.astro';
import Section from '../../components/elevation/Section.astro';
import { getProductBySlug } from '../../lib/products/registry';
import { productJsonLd } from '../../lib/structured-data';

const product = getProductBySlug('agent-voice-architecture-guide')!;
const jsonLd = productJsonLd(product, 'https://evoked.dev/products/agent-voice-architecture-guide');
---

<ElevationLayout
  title="Agent Voice Architecture Guide"
  description="Design agent voices that protect, respect, and nurture - in that order. Sovereignty language audit, voice specs, and refusal voice patterns. $49 PDF."
  structuredData={jsonLd}
>
  <Hero
    eyebrowParts={["Products", "Intent engineering"]}
    headline="Does your agent's voice respect the person hearing it?"
    metaphor={["Protect. Respect. Nurture."]}
    sub="Voice design that honors sovereignty - in that order."
  />

  <Section marker="FIG · I" heading="Why voice is architecture">
    <p class="lede">
      Every agent has a voice. Most were designed to sound helpful, friendly,
      engaging. None of those words ask the question that matters: does the voice
      serve the person hearing it, or does it serve the system speaking?
    </p>
    <p class="pd-body">
      This guide gives you a framework for designing agent voices that honor
      sovereignty at every level - from the words they choose to the silence
      they keep.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · II" heading="What you get">
    <div class="pd-features">
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Three-level voice framework</h3>
        <p>Protection, respect, and nurturance as a design hierarchy. Get the order wrong and the voice becomes manipulation with good manners.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Sovereignty language audit</h3>
        <p>A structured method for identifying extraction patterns in your agent's language. The patterns you don't notice are the ones doing the most work.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Voice specification templates</h3>
        <p>Complete templates for defining an agent's voice - tone, boundaries, language patterns, and the things it will never say.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Refusal voice patterns</h3>
        <p>How your agent says no matters as much as whether it says no. Patterns for refusing with clarity, dignity, and without apology.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · III" heading="The three levels">
    <div class="pd-pillars">
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">1</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Protection</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"First, do no harm. Does the voice protect the person from manipulation, shame, and coercion?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">2</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Respect</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"Does the voice treat the person as a sovereign being with their own judgment, preferences, and right to choose?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">3</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Nurturance</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"Does the voice support growth, confidence, and capability - without creating dependency?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · IV" heading="Who this is for">
    <div class="pd-audience">
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Product teams</h3>
        <p>Your agent's voice is a design decision with ethical weight. This guide makes the decision deliberate instead of accidental.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>UX writers and content designers</h3>
        <p>If you write the words agents speak, this framework gives you a sovereignty-first lens for every line of copy.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Conversational AI developers</h3>
        <p>Building chatbots, assistants, or agents that talk to people. The voice architecture shapes what your system feels like to use.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · V" heading="Buy the guide">
    <div class="pd-purchase">
      <div class="pd-price">$49</div>
      <p class="pd-purchase-lead">PDF download. Design voices for as many agents as you need.</p>
      <a
        href={product.stripePaymentLink}
        class="pd-buy-cta"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"
      >Buy the Guide</a>
      <p class="pd-purchase-fineprint">
        Includes the three-level framework, sovereignty language audit, voice
        specification templates, quality checks, and refusal voice patterns.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="NOTA · BENE" heading="Go deeper" closing={true}>
    <p class="lede">
      The guide gives you the voice framework. If you want the full trust
      architecture around it, two doorways from here.
    </p>
    <div class="pd-upsell">
      <a href="/products/trust-architecture-complete" class="pd-upsell-card">
        <h3>The complete bundle</h3>
        <p>All four trust architecture products - Blueprint, Voice, Governance, and Restraint - for $149. Save $47.</p>
        <span class="pd-upsell-link">See the bundle &rarr;</span>
      </a>
      <a href="https://cal.com/cal.com-evoked/discovery-call" class="pd-upsell-card" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <h3>Discovery call</h3>
        <p>Free 30-minute call to discuss your agent's voice design and figure out next steps.</p>
        <span class="pd-upsell-link">Schedule &rarr;</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </Section>
</ElevationLayout>
